# 57
{570}{}{The Woodcutter's Note}
{571}{}{	Some may think I've gone mad, some will think I've lost my mind. But the fact remains - after being struck by lightning I decided to leave all my treasures to whoever finds this place. But I don't want it to be found all that easily, so you'll have to use your head and work with your hands to find my precious. So let's begin without long introductions. I won't see you suffer anyway, so I won't invent any pretty riddles for you.
	If you find the water source - you'll find the next clue too.

[Entry added later]

	Hello, Wanderer. We, the Children of the Wasteland, found the woodcutter's treasure, but it's unlikely to interest you. So in exchange we've left our own. We once gathered and rested here together, but now there's simply no time for that, so we're hardly ever around. The Wasteland is our home.

[The recording is badly distorted by interference]

Good luck in your search for treasure!}

# 58
{580}{}{The CW in Faces. Part 1}
{581}{}{Look for trouble where you'd never even suspect it...

[Due to the holodisk's poor quality, part of the recording is corrupted and cannot be read]

	LoadRunner
	Because of the replications, the past is gradually forgotten.
	Born in a little-known miners' settlement; his father was crippled after yet another cave-in at the mine and had to look for new work. As a result - a move to Klamath and the start of a new life.
	At 18 LoadRunner goes off to Arroyo after some shaman, so the man would teach him the wisdom of healing. After three years the training ends, but he doesn't want to go home. He gets an offer to help with healing for a group of people whose goal is to help anyone and everyone. Gradually LoadRunner becomes one of their own in this company. Around the same time came a meeting that determined the healer's further fate - he met a real doctor who took him to the VC and taught him more serious things. After the training LoadRunner makes his first medical mistake - he falls in love with his patient and later marries her. By that time the group of guys in which LoadRunner hones his skills gradually becomes a respected and serious organization.
	Likes to carve wood, doesn't smoke, doesn't drink, often remembers his parents and visits them from time to time. Bad habits - talks a lot. Always carries medicine and tools, wears boots in any weather, carries an axe on his belt. Likes to wear a robe - it's roomy, protects from the wind and from the scorching rays of the sun.

	Nazir, also known as Naz, also known as Nazirka and Turdy, was born in a cozy tent near Junktown that had a hole of an interesting shape. Well, at least that's where he appeared, since the farmers who found the baby couldn't find any human tracks anywhere. The oddities and mysteries were pushed into the background, for the boy was unbelievably handsome, if you compared him to a deathclaw of the same age.
	The years went by, Naz grew into a man, becoming as harsh as a roll of sandpaper slipped into the local outhouse by some joker. Nazir never figured out who. The first occupation of the stern Junktown handyman was - oddly enough - repairing equipment and various primus stoves, and that everywhere, always, and under any circumstances.
In time, his soul thirsting for romance had a big falling-out with his backside seeking adventure, and two limbs in heavy boots carried the lad across the world, inflicting good and dealing joy upon those around him. Town after town he visited, gifting those less fortunate gecko-hide jackets, submachine guns, and if the day was a good one - a fine little machine gun too. His second occupation, after repairs, was winding the local fauna and some flora around the barrel of his minigun. At the same time he never stopped helping those who really needed help.
	Arroyo became his destiny; it was there he met Yuppie, a girl from the Children of the Wasteland. He doesn't remember the whole meeting in detail; only a few words of the conversation and the stars in the sky are imprinted in his memory. And, of course, the tits, can't do without those.
	Gradually, having become a full-fledged Child of the Wasteland - and he's certain he was born of the wasteland itself, just like his younger brother Savior - Nazir became more than just someone who helped one and all. As more people came wanting to join the CW, he willy-nilly had to become daddy to the newcomers, helping and training them for the harsh life in the wasteland. What they say about him afterward remains a mystery, but after the third bottle Naz couldn't care less.

Yuppie...

[After this the recording suddenly cuts off]}

# 59
{590}{}{The CW in Faces. Part 2}
{591}{}{HE who knows the alphabet - HE knows where to look next.

The following recording was stolen by who knows whom, by an unknown means. And it reached us in an inconceivable way. The original recording was of poor quality, so the copy doesn't differ much.

From the Hubologists' archives:
[Part of the recording is corrupted]
On the whole, subject number 3893 continues to work quite successfully for us and for the "Punisher's Rangers"... so for now our plans do not include disconnecting him from the replication system.

Uncle Ztsuk
Replication subject number 3894.
All of us were somewhat unsettled by the fact that this young man came to replication already having at least a hundred and fifty deaths in his "replication register gene" (or, as we call it, his "counter"). Before this interesting discovery we considered him an ordinary madman, of which there are many in the Wasteland. Of course! Some strange ragamuffin shows up at our head office and says that danger threatens us and all of humanity. Even now it's hard to believe that our experiment in playing God will fail. But the facts speak for themselves. Naturally, the most skeptical among us suppose that he somehow stole the blueprints or even the apparatus itself from one of our first stations. I'm tired of explaining to them that they're wrong. No human could gather enough biomaterial to replicate that many times. According to his testimony, soon all replicants will get out of control, having lost their fear of death. It will be the Grand Slaughter - he said it exactly like that, as if both words were written with capital letters. I tried to study his phenomenon and found that he can alter the flow of time, as if "borrowing" it from others; then of course he has to "give it back," losing his own. It's simply ASTOUNDING! If we could give the same abilities to our people, we would become invincible. Of course, at first I didn't believe him either, but I quickly changed my mind... damn it, he just walked up to me with a calm face and slapped me, ME!!! AHB-7!!!, across the cheeks, but I just stood there and couldn't move... The most interesting thing is that after his appearance at our replication station, similar abilities began to manifest in some people as well... in some they appear to almost the same degree. In others only in case of danger (some replicants have learned to control the process and use this "bonus" to calmly mow down herds(!) of centaurs)...
[Part of the recording is corrupted]
...lately he's often been spotted with members of the "Children of the Wasteland" group. Yet another sect. Their unofficial leader (replicant number 4104) lays out some pictograms on the ground and calls them pictures. Another one (rather, a woman - replicant number 7518) possesses either the gift of persuasion or hypnosis... in short, she's constantly followed by an army of weaklings who haven't yet managed to get used to their replicated bodies... over time this effect passes and people's skills, lost during the first "Recording" and "mounting" of the "counter," return to them. Third on the list but not in importance, the "leader" is quite friendly, but sometimes he has spontaneous bursts of rage, and that, combined with the fact that he possesses the greatest firepower of all of them, can turn out rather deplorably. The main plus - he calms down quickly. The main minus - he's so strange that sometimes even his "brothers in the cult" can't understand him. And that sometimes leads to rather sad "incidents" (his number - 6459)...
[Part of the recording is corrupted]
...Recently I had a talk with this Uncle. He said that maintaining neutrality is the key to preventing the Grand Slaughter, since man is by his very nature a greedy creature. Even a kind man sometimes wants killings, just as a killer sometimes grows tired of killing. His phrase "I love everyone very much, which is why I'll mess with everyone with equal force" shook my worldview. I'll try to wring a couple of free replications out of the bosses for these "Children of the Wasteland."
[Part of the recording is corrupted]
Dug up in storage the watch he came to us with on his "first" time... last time he asked to find his "Symbol of Time," I'll need to give it to him.
Ugh, time's running ou...
[Here the recording cuts off]}

# 60
{600}{}{The CW in Faces. Part 3}
{601}{}{	Name: Nimms
	Biography: Born November 3, 2209, in the small town of Klamath. His father was a trapper and often took his son hunting. Excellent perception, incredible agility, and unique intelligence - all of this showed in him already in childhood. He was utterly unable to socialize. He grew more slowly than other children. Upon turning 18 he went off into the Wasteland in hopes of earning a living. After several years of wandering he decided to return home. By that time Klamath had been seized by the so-called Zergs - a large gang of bandits who spared no one. When Nimms was only a few steps from death, he met a man in combat armor. His name was Caps and he was one of the Knights of the Wasteland. What Caps told him about Klamath's fate was a great blow to Nimms. He had lost all his loved ones. Caps comforted him and offered to keep him company. Nimms agreed. And they wandered the desert together for a long time, helping unfortunate people. Over the course of their joint travels Nimms gained experience and learned to handle weapons. Caps became his best friend. But one day Caps received a message from his superiors saying he had to report to headquarters urgently. After saying goodbye, Caps left Nimms his radio as a keepsake. They never saw each other again. One day, trying to catch a frequency on the radio over which he could contact Caps, he stumbled onto the channel of an organization called the Children of the Wasteland. From their conversations he learned that this organization were peacekeepers helping people survive the harsh conditions of the Wasteland. Then he, deciding to continue the cause he and Caps had shared, became one of the Children himself, and remains so to this day, sacrificing himself for the well-being of others.
	Over the course of his adventures with Caps he perfected his repair skills, becoming a jack-of-all-trades. His difficult character became his main flaw. Distinguishing marks - a large scar on his left cheek, wears a leather jacket, carries a shotgun over his shoulder.

	Name: MORFY
	Biography: Date, place, and time of manufacture unknown. He came to consciousness in a huge ruined city, clutching an army knife in his right hand. He could read, write, count - in short, everything that normal and abnormal people can do, only speaking didn't work out for him (more precisely, he didn't know how to do it at all). For a long time he lived and wandered in complete solitude across the boundless, as it seemed at the time, post-nuclear urban landscape, finding useful things and old food (oddly enough, it was still edible). Once, in one of the apartments of the megalopolis, he found a book on marksmanship and an old oiled rifle on the lap of a corpse, or rather a skeleton. In the decayed rags of prewar clothing he found a note with the address of a country house. Navigating by old, worn-out signs, he trudged out of the city. Thinking about his future, he kept walking north, only north, in search of the cherished house. After 47 moons he came upon a small village (which turned out to be Arroyo). Tired and exhausted, forgetting all caution, he entered the settlement. In the middle of the road stood two people - a young man and a young woman. Noticing the stranger, they said: "Hi!". "Hi," he answered them (extraordinary sensations rushed through his brain). "Come with us," they offered...

	Name: Bashmak
	Biography: "Gecko Boots" - that was exactly the sign that hung on his father's shop in the Hub, and thanks to it Bashmak got his nickname. Over the years he grew so accustomed to his nickname that he himself could barely recall the name given to him at birth. From an early age Bashmak helped his father in his shop and learned to work lizard and brahmin hides quite well. Growing up, he began to explore the area around the Hub, hunting and harvesting hides. One day he realized that in the wasteland he felt a special freedom and could easily stay out on trips for weeks, only occasionally returning to the city to give his father the material he'd gathered. A good knowledge of the Wasteland's wildlife and of the location of dangerous and safe places made him an excellent guide, so after his father's death he, without much hesitation, sold the shop and set off north. One fine day in Arroyo he came across a group of people whose goal was to help those in need and who aided young hunters and explorers. Seeing kindred spirits in them, Bashmak gladly joined.......

	Name: Kostyanych
	Biography: November 22, 2242... a sweltering desert wind was literally burying our caravan, heading up from the south, in radioactive sand. I and several of my friends were relocating north in search of a new and better life. Moving away from the ruins of the Mariposa mutant base, we had almost reached that fabled city described in the books of legend as the paradise city - Arroyo. It was the last stage of our journey, but, as often happens in the uncharted wasteland, our caravan fell into a raiders' ambush... we fought back to the last bullet, but the odds were uneven; suddenly a group of people calling themselves the Children of the Wasteland rushed to our aid... the further course and the end of that battle I remember only from my rescuers' accounts... With bloody, torn wounds, barefoot and almost without clothing, I was brought to their refuge. They called it the Little Cave; I'd never encountered anything cozier until then and was pleasantly surprised by their hospitality and the genuinely humane treatment I received. These people gave me everything - both shelter and clothing. The most precious item, which remains so for me to this day, is the boots that more than once saved me from radioactive puddles, and a weapon, so I could always defend myself and my loved ones from attack from outside and help others like the one I once was myself. Since then I became one of the Children of the Wasteland...

	Name: Ziga
	Biography: I was born in the city of New Reno, and that's a city of big opportunities and big guns. Its glittering lights draw crowds of adventure-seekers, but the story of most of them ends at Golgotha. And all because the city is run by the Families, and it'll go badly for anyone who doesn't want to play by their rules...
	But we played. We spent money at the casino, especially my mother, who also worked there, serving all sorts of lucky bandits and dashing soldiers who at one and the same table would now drink cheap beer, now cut each other's throats.
	I was raised for the most part by my father; ah, what a man he was. He was very sad when I was born, for he wanted a little boy, and he even went on a bender. That was when I began to take an interest in his affairs. To ask how his hunt had gone or whether there was any news from other cities. Gradually my father taught me to hunt. To throw stones from a homemade sling, or how to survive in the wasteland. My mother paid me no attention at all, and that was very hurtful. At times there was nothing to eat and I had to steal. Lying in wait for a long time under various heaps of garbage for passersby to stop in the shade to rest. Then I'd dart out and cut the purses off careless people or snatch the more valuable things...
... 6 years later ...
Wandering the wastes alone is certain death, so, having sold everything valuable to the first caravaneer and bought a ticket from him, a new road awaited us. That it was time for me to clear out, they declared just a few days later near a clogged and half-ruined mining town - unless, of course, I wanted to pay for the ticket with my body. So, slamming the rifle butt into the caravaneer's fat mug and ripping the pouch off his belt, I took off running. Roaming the dirty streets without looking ahead, trouble caught up with me again, or so it seemed at the time, but no - this young man, "Lurik," was very courteous and, noticing that before him was a girl, started apologizing himself and even invited me into his house. I had both a weapon and money in case I needed to buy my way out, so I quickly agreed.
... some time later ...
And so I was accepted into the Children of the Wasteland, on my 14th birthday... I'm glad of this event...
I'd like to say thanks to Yuppie, who was the first to start telling me about the laws of survival in the Southern lands and the methods of fighting centaurs...
To PSYCHO, who dragged me along the caravans...
To Kubik for the Big-Bada-Boom...
And to everyone, everyone, everyone....
	Thanks to Lurik for introducing me to the Children of the Wasteland... I haven't seen him since then, by the way, but it's all still ahead - for in the wasteland wishes come true...

	Name: Lesnichy (the Forester)
	Biography: Year and place of birth unknown; he remembers his parents only vaguely - they died after yet another marauder raid. The little boy fled into the forest, where he lived, feeding on berries and roots.
One day in the forest he met a hunter named Smiley, who taught the boy to skin geckos and wild brahmin, to shoot accurately, and gave him a map of the Wasteland. From then on the boy traveled the Wasteland a great deal, very rarely entering the cities. He never forgot his forest and always returned to it as to his home, and so he was nicknamed the Forester. During one of his travels he met a man on an iron cart out in the desert. That's how he met the mechanic Smitty. Smitty taught the Forester repair. But the youth (by that
time the forest-dweller looked about 20 years old) particularly enjoyed assembling weapons, armor, ammunition, and many different useful things out of junk and other unwanted items. So the Forester became a crafter-repairman...
	During his travels he heard much good about the Children of the Wasteland, and wanted to become one of them himself, for he too had always helped people however he could. Meeting Kubik one day, the Forester became convinced of the truth of the rumors about the CW, and was happy when he soon became one of the members of this organization.

	He who knows the Forest - holds the inFOrmation.}

# 61
{610}{}{Anthem of the Children of the Wasteland}
{611}{}{In the post-nuclear world,
Where the climate is harsh,
We live not in a flat,
Here the sky is our roof,
Sheltering under the leaves,
We sleep on the ground,
Washing in the dew,
We rise at dawn.

Chorus:
Wasteland, we are your children,
We answer for you,
We don't even spare ourselves
For you.

We help everyone
Who has asked us,
We rescue from troubles
As long as our strength holds.
And we are respected,
Called upon for help,
But we are killed
For our peaceful labor.

Wasteland, we are your children,
We answer for you,
We don't even spare ourselves
For you.

But still with hope
We gaze upon the Wasteland,
And just as before
We'll conquer misfortune,
And the Wasteland will forget
Both grief and pain,
And let ours be
The role of saviors!

Wasteland, we are your children,
We answer for you,
We don't even spare ourselves
For you.

One last step remains - to find the treasure. Remember that the passage to the treasury often opens from afar - an inconspicuous floor tile, a book in a cabinet, or the knot of some tree...
If luck smiles on you - you'll be able to find the treasure.}

