# 100
{1000}{}{The Church of Brock and Zander. Official information about the organization.}
{1001}{}{Creed:
The followers of the Church honor and worship the all-good Gardener Gods, Brock the Great and his Brother, Zander - the merciful patrons of crafters, healers, traders, and warriors noble in spirit. In their great condescension, the Gardener Gods incline their ear to the prayers of the faithful who ask for luck and success, sustaining the spirit and strengthening the will.
But abhorrent to Them are the embodiments of evil and destruction - base thugs, contemptible thieves, and vile "martyrs"; loathsome are killings "for fun," mockery, and abuse. But the righteous path, filled with mercy and aid, labor and care for one's neighbors, is pleasing to the Gardeners, and in their mercy they sent people their gifts - the Brock Flower and the Zander Root, the Blooming and the Growing.
From these flowers, healers make powders and stimpaks, and crafters - through their labor - raise their skills; and a trader may fearlessly carry with him even 100 flowers, even a thousand - they have no weight and are convenient on the road.
A believer in the Gardeners is free in his deeds, but is obliged to observe the Sacred Commandments:
1. Renounce thuggery - thugs are loathsome to Zander the Merciful.
2. Renounce theft from people, for this grave sin angers Brock the Great.
3. Help those in need, honor our Gods, respect fellow believers, and strive to lead a worthy life, committing no senseless destruction and not increasing evil.
The Church of Brock and Zander is not a sect, nor an Order. We, the followers, do not seek to impose our faith across the whole Wasteland and to "exterminate the unbelievers."
Those wishing to believe and join take on no other obligations than the observance of the Three Commandments. Whether to carry the Word of the Gods to other places, whether to take part in the activities of the Church,
to preach and perform acts of devotion - is the follower's own choice. It should also be added that membership in the Community carries no special privileges, except those
that a believer earns through his own righteousness - the gratitude and respect of those around him.}

# 101
{1010}{}{Sermon On Death.}
{1011}{}{I wish to address you, brothers and sisters.
The subject will be an unusual one.
The subject of Death.
We are all mortal. Anyone can die. Be he even a terminator-fighter of the highest skill.
Do not fear death. The body is perishable.
Do not fear losing your ammunition. All that can be earned again.
But...
Never show the killer a negative reaction or emotion. That is what he is waiting for.
The Gods and Admins have given us three minutes for the time while the Spirit migrates into a new body, and during this time your Spirit can express thoughts and emotions.
I call upon You.
To turn these minutes of peace into prayer or pity for the victim.
For this person is worthy of pity. His spirit is dead. He is weak and filled with fear, for he has no Faith.}

# 102
{1020}{}{Sermon On Character.}
{1021}{}{The Church of Brock and Zander.
Many ask, where does your strong spirit come from? It is raised by faith and character.
Character is defined by the values by which you guide your life. When we speak of bad character, we mean either a lack of upbringing or that a person looks at the world through the prism of false values. If you listen only to what the flesh dictates to you, you will bring harm both to yourself and to others.
If the thoughts are filthy, a person is damaged within, corrupted. One must cleanse one's thoughts, and then bad character too will change. It is important to shape it consciously.
Character is more important than wealth, more significant than any position in society. Cultivate righteous character within yourself!
Character is mightier than success; work on it, nurture it.
Character lasts longer than popularity, is better than a good name, because as soon as your character fails you, your good name will vanish.
Character is the foundation on which we build.
We are the Church of Brock and Zander.}

# 103
{1030}{}{Sermon On the God-Forsaken.}
{1031}{}{The Church of Brock and Zander.
Look around you! What do you see? Who stands in your way? I will answer: the God-forsaken thugs.
Let your eyes be opened! Let your hearts be opened!
As ours have been opened.
Stop the God-forsaken deeds through us!
Let us take up arms and, turning to our Gods in prayer, show Our strength. Each knows the sphere of life he is called to influence, so that the road there may be barred to the God-forsaken.
Let our strength revive each one, that we may do good. Affirm good through us, so that the God-forsaken one becomes disarmed.
By our hands, by our loving hearts, must this good deed be done!
Join our ranks, find Faith, and with it the will and strength of spirit.}

# 104
{1040}{}{Sermon On Conduct.}
{1041}{}{The Church of Brock and Zander.
We charge you, brethren, to keep away from every rabble that behaves outrageously.
Do you like being wretched? Do you like being among the wretched?
You must be especially disciplined. It does not matter how others behave - what matters is what you do.
Examine yourselves, repent of your transgressions. For outrage and boorishness come shame and disgrace, infirmity and sickness, failure and defeat.
I pray that all may be cultured people, that they never act outrageously, and I ask our Gods for special grace for those who thirst for this.}

# 105
{1050}{}{The Myth of the Peaceful Neutral.}
{1051}{}{It happened in a faraway little village.
The people there lived modestly, decently, and peacefully - whenever it worked out, of course.
The raids of the God-forsaken raiders they beat off, just as they toiled by the sweat of their brow - together, and each was ready to take the place of a wounded comrade; no one tried to sit it out in the cellar.
There were many people there, both old and young, and some still quite small.
And in that settlement there lived a young woman.
She knew all manner of herbs, healed people,
and was very beautiful.
And for her herbs she would go far out into the wasteland, alone.
And into various troubles, as often happens with lone wanderers, she did not fall,
or if she did, no one in the village ever heard of it.
And it would have gone on like that for a long time,
but one day
a swift-footed, curious boy
secretly set off after her, unseen by all.
And he discovered
that this healer went to the ferocious bandits,
and spoke with them,
and healed them after the raids they made on her own native village,
and traded her young body there.
That is why she had so little trouble on the road - the raiders did not touch her, for even they need healing, and a soft girl's body was pleasing to them.
And so the people gathered,
and questioned her.
That she went to the raiders, she did not deny.
But she insisted there was no guilt upon her.
For she herself raised a hand against no one;
on the contrary, she healed everyone, did good, after all.
And the people began to murmur, yet they could not reach a clear decision.
And the people called for two glorious brothers, that they might judge this situation; Brock and Zander were their names.
And the brothers came, and began to deliberate and question the people. And so the turn came to the healer.
And then Brock asked,
- How long have you lived in this settlement, woman, how long have you known these people?
And the healer answered that she had lived here since birth, and had long known and respected all these people.
And Brock asked - when the raiders come, these people suffer from wounds and die; is that good?
And the healer answered - no, it pains me to see their suffering, and so I heal these unfortunate people. For the raiders' raids I am not to blame; such is their dark nature.
- Then why do you go and heal these killers? For they make raids upon your sisters and brothers. - Brock demanded.
- They too are people, and suffer no less. And the raids I cannot stop, for they are strong and rough, while I am only a weak woman who knows herbs. - she answered.
And Brock furrowed his brows, and said.
- It is not because you pity their suffering that you heal our enemies. But because you wish to please both sides, and to live well, so that they leave you personally alone.
You have forgotten the face of your father, and your mother just as easily you would sell,
if only to live better and safer than you do now.
Go to your raiders. For you are repugnant to all these people, and you fear even to look them in the face; they do not wish to see you here, beside them. And as for healing them, my brother Zander can do that. For we wished just now to rest from our travels, and our help will be no burden to you.
And the glorious brothers came to live in that settlement.
As for the healer - she went off wherever her eyes led her, and never returned there again.
But the people said that in the end she did repent after all,
and found herself shelter and a hearth in some other village, where her dark past was unknown.
And there she lived rightly, honoring not only the laws, but also thinking of those who lived beside her, and not only of herself.}

# 106
{1060}{}{Soldier's Diary}
{1061}{}{Entry 22
Today our squad is patrolling the northern part of the California Republic, where the activity of surviving mutants is still observed. For days now we have been following the trail of the largest group. They left behind mountains of corpses: people, animals, and sometimes mutants.

Entry 23
We came upon a small building. Inside it - a passage underground. Below is something like an underground bunker or an abandoned base. We took up combat positions and surveyed the area. Monstrous images come to mind, for not so far from here there once was the Master's vault. The very thought of it is chilling.

Entry 24
I'm writing this entry in haste. At night I woke to gunfire and screams. It looks like the mutants caught us with our pants down. Only three of us are left: me, our commander Colonel Petrenko, and one recruit. I was badly wounded in the neck; we hid behind the corpses of our fallen comrades, and they are searching for us... (entry cut off)
}


# 107
{1070}{}{Trapper's Diary}
{1071}{}{
Entry 1
This season, rumor has it there are a great many geckos in the north. Found an old abandoned cave, moved my things there, and started hunting nearby. A devilishly rich haul. I imagined how much I could afford by selling the hides.

Entry 2
Met a traveler; he didn't look like a bandit, but when we got close he raised a shotgun and I caught a load of buckshot in the leg. When I came to, I noticed my knife, water flask, and bag of hides were gone. On the way back a wolf attacked me, must have sensed easy prey. I dealt with it bare-handed, barely survived.

Entry 3
The leg has swollen badly and turned blue; I'll have to amputate so the rot doesn't reach my heart. Looks like I let an infection in through the wound.

Entry 4
Hard to breathe, the infection has spread to my lungs. There was nothing I could do. I can't walk, I can't get out of the cave. What an irony of fate - a trapper, trapped by a snare set by fate itself...}

# 108
{1080}{}{Notes of a Madman}
{1081}{}{Year 2078. January 17.
My name is James... James Redfield. I am the only resident of Vault 77. I don't understand why a whole vault was allotted to me alone, even if a smaller one, but I'm pleased that I got what I paid for. Quite recently the nuclear warheads fell on the heads of those who remained above, sweeping away our past. I suppose I feel sorry for them.

Year 2078. February 24.
I fear mistakes were made by the company; among the supplies there is nothing to occupy myself with except a box of glove puppets. This troubles me somewhat, for I asked that as many books as possible be placed in the storeroom.

Year 2078. May 21.
To occupy myself somehow, I began to play with these puppets; one of them was different from the others... I named it Mr. Hendley. When I was playing with Mr. Hendley once again, he spoke to me - how is that possible? I don't know, but it was definitely him. I feel I'm going mad...

Year 2078. July 7.
Mr. Hendley is my only friend; I think I can trust him. Now I have someone to talk to, someone to argue with, and a way to occupy myself. Now I have a companion, and that's the best thing there could be.

Year 2078. October 3.
Hendley said that I am a government experiment. He thinks I'm being watched, though I had long felt it myself. I can't stay here any longer, I must flee. When I came out of the vault, I felt the sun; for a whole year I had forgotten what the sun was. This place used to look different, but now it was as if I were in a desert... I had never left the vault before, but now the way back is closed to me too. Hendley and I must go, I don't know where, but I would like to find civilization.

Year 2078. December 25.
I don't know what came over me... As I wandered the desert in search of water and people, in the distance I saw several people walking toward me; I was glad of them. When I approached I asked for water and they kindly shared it, then someone struck me on the back of the head... I came to in a small cave, bound and helpless, and those kindly people were already preparing a fire; there were bones everywhere and I foresaw my fate. I had already given up, but not Hendley. My friend was full of resolve; he guided and inspired me. He said we must win... The blood boiled in my veins, fury overwhelmed me. I slowly crawled to the edge of the cave and cut the ropes on one of the sharp rocks. When those bandits lit the fire, one of them came toward me; I tore through the rest of the rope, snatched the knife from behind his belt and slit his throat, and when the second one ran at me, I simply drove the knife into his chest and fled. I don't know how I did it; in any other situation I would never have brought myself to such a thing. Perhaps it's all the influence of Mr. Hendley...

Year 2080.
I've already lost count of the days. I cannot forget what happened about a year ago; I killed two men, and since then Hendley has been the one guiding me. It's strange, but he helped me survive; I killed animals, I lived in a cave, I myself became practically an animal. Today Hendley made me kill some traveler; I was hungry and I did it... I can't believe it. I'm not ready for such a life, and I think I must tell Hendley this.

Added 2 days later.
I told Hendley that we can't live like this, that we need to find other people and live with them. He grew angry; he said that the last time we saw people, they tried to kill us, and although that's true, there must still be good people left in the world. Hendley wouldn't even listen to me; he decided that I couldn't survive without him and said I could go. Even if I don't survive, I'll die a man, not an animal. I left Hendley in that cave and set off in search of my humanity.

Added 10 days later.
I'm trapped. Hendley was right... By chance I ended up in the wrong place at the wrong time. It was to be expected. I'm writing this entry in the hope that someone will find my remains and remember me as one who did not betray himself, as one who remained a man in this cruel world.
}

